ferc_filing_data.tariff_title: Newmont Nevada Energy Investment LLC FERC Electric Tariff

record_data.record_plain_text: 1. Availability: Nevada Gold Energy LLC (NGE) makes electric energy and capacity available under this FERC Electric Tariff (the Tariff) for wholesale sales. NGE also makes available under this Tariff certain products and ancillary services, subject to the limitations below. A. California Independent System Operator Cooperation (California ISO): NGE offers Replacement Reserves and the following ancillary services: (i) Regulation Service, (ii) Spinning Reserve Service, and (iii) Non-Spinning Reserve Service to the California ISO and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the California ISO. B. Other Markets: In markets in the Western Interconnection other than those administered by the California ISO, NGE offers Regulation Service, Energy Imbalance Service, Spinning Reserves and Supplemental Reserves subject to establishing an Internet-based site that will (a) set forth procedures under which all customers would request service and make bids, (b) include postings, prior to making transactions, of offers of services available and their offering prices, (c) include prompt postings of the actual transaction prices after ancillary services transactions are consummated, and (d) include posting information about accepted and denied requests and the reasons for denial. C. Other Service: NGE may sell other ancillary services into markets administered by the California ISO and in other geographic markets in the Western Interconnection to the extent that the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (Commission) grants authority on a blanket basis to make sales of such services to all persons then authorized to make sales at market-based rates. D. Prohibitions. In markets in the Western Interconnection other than those administered by the California ISO, NGE will not sell ancillary services under this Tariff to (a) a regional transmission organization (RTO) such as an independent system operator (ISO) or a transco, i.e., where the RTO has no ability to self-supply these services but instead depends on third parties, (b) any franchised public utility affiliated with NGE, or to customers where the transmission service is on the franchised public utility affiliates system, (c) a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers. 2. Reassignment of Transmission Capacity: NGE may reassign transmission capacity that it has reserved for its own use at a price not to exceed the highest of: (a) the original transmission rate paid by NGE; (b) the applicable transmission providers maximum stated firm transmission rate on file at the time of the transmission reassignment; or (c) NGEs own opportunity costs, capped at the applicable transmission providers cost of expansion at the time of the sale to the eligible customer. NGE will not recover opportunity costs in connection with reassignments without making a separate filing under Section 205 of the FPA. Except for the price, the terms and conditions under which the reassignment is made shall be the terms and conditions governing the original grant by the transmission provider. Transmission capacity may only be reassigned to a customer eligible to take service under the transmission providers open access transmission tariff or other transmission rate schedules. NGE will report the name of the assignee in its quarterly reports. 3. Resale of Firm Transmission Rights: NGE may resell Firm Transmission Rights (FTRs) and other comparable products, whether financial or physical in nature, that it has acquired for its own benefit at a price not to exceed any caps imposed by the Commission in its orders authorizing the issuance of such FTRs. Except for the price, the terms and conditions under which the resale is made shall be the terms and conditions governing the original grant by the transmission provider. NGE will report the names of any purchasers in its quarterly reports. 4. Applicability: This Tariff is applicable to all sales by NGE of energy, capacity, ancillary services, or other products identified in paragraphs 1-3. 5. Rates: All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and NGE, subject to any limitations set forth in paragraphs 1-3. 6. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between NGE and the purchaser. 7. Prohibited Sales: No sale may be made pursuant to this Tariff to any affiliate of NGE with a franchised service territory without first receiving Commission approval under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act, 16 U.S.C. 824d. 8. Reporting Requirement: NGE must timely report to the Commission any change in status that would reflect a departure from the characteristics the Commission relied upon in granting market-based rate authority. A change in status includes, but is not limited to, each of the following: (i) ownership or control of generation or transmission facilities or inputs to electric power production other than fuel supplies, or (ii) affiliation with an entity not disclosed in the application for market-based rate authority that owns or controls generation or transmission facilities or inputs to electric power production, or affiliation with any entity that has a franchised service area. Any change in status must be filed no later than 30 days after the change in status occurs. 9. Effective Date: This Tariff is effective on July 29, 2006 or such earlier date as the Commission may establish.
